Notes & questions

  • From GATK VariantsToTable docs:
    • TRANSITION (1 for a bi-allelic transition (SNP), 0 for bi-allelic transversion (SNP), -1 for INDELs and multi-allelics)
    • NO-CALL (count of no-call genotypes)
    • VAR (count of non-reference genotypes)
  • Need to plot
    • Mean coverage per site (Yassine says limit to 8)
    • GQ per site (Yassine says limit to 20)
  • Re: Phred scale: “For many purposes, a Phred Score of 20 or above is acceptable, because this means that whatever it qualifies is 99% accurate, with a 1% chance of error.”

Setup

sample_metadata <- read_csv(here::here("data/derived_data/metadata/bovine_demo.sample_metadata.csv"))
eval_28 <-
  c("1kbulls_tranche100", "bovine_demo", "post") %>%
  purrr::set_names("1kbulls_tranche100", "demo_pre", "demo_post") %>%
  purrr::map_dfr(
    ~ read_table2(here::here(glue::glue("data/derived_data/joint_genotyping/filter_eval/filter_eval.{.x}.28.table"))) %>%
      left_join(read_table2(here::here(glue::glue("data/derived_data/joint_genotyping/filter_eval/filter_eval.{.x}.28.ldepth.mean")))),
    .id = "dataset") %>%
  select(-CHROM, -TYPE) %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()
with_indels <-
  read_table2(here::here("data/derived_data/joint_genotyping/filter_eval/filter_eval.with_indels.table")) %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()
nocalls <-
  eval_28 %>% 
  select(dataset, pos, no_call) 
gq <-
  c("1kbulls_tranche100", "1kbulls_tranche99", "1kbulls_tranche90", "bovine_demo", "post") %>%
  purrr::set_names("1kbulls_tranche100", "1kbulls_tranche99", "1kbulls_tranche90", "demo_pre", "demo_post") %>%
  purrr::map2_dfr(
    .y = c(4933, 4933, 4933, 2766, 2364),
    ~ read_table2(here::here(glue::glue("data/derived_data/joint_genotyping/filter_eval/filter_eval.{.x}.28_random.GQ.FORMAT")), na = ".") %>%
      tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = all_of(3:.y),
                          names_to = "international_id",
                          values_to = "gq"),
    .id = "dataset") %>% 
  janitor::clean_names() %>% 
  select(-chrom)

How many SNPs within 5 bp of an indel?

indel_range <- 
  with_indels %>% 
  filter(type == "INDEL") %>% 
  select(pos) %>% 
  mutate(list = purrr::map(.x = pos, ~ seq(from = .x-5, to = .x+5))) %>% 
  unnest(list) %>% 
  pull(list)

247,195 of 3,315,789 total SNPs are within 5 bp of an indel (7.46%).

Filter values prior to QC

Quality by depth

  • “QUAL: The Phred-scaled probability that a REF/ALT polymorphism exists at this site given sequencing data. Because the Phred scale is -10 x log(1-p), a value of 10 indicates a 1 in 10 chance of error, while a 100 indicates a 1 in 10^10 chance (see the FAQ article for a detailed explanation). These values can grow very large when a large amount of data is used for variant calling, so QUAL is not often a very useful property for evaluating the quality of a variant call. Not to be confused with the sample-level annotation GQ; see this FAQ article for an explanation of the differences in what they mean and how they should be used.”
  • “QUAL tells you how confident we are that there is some kind of variation at a given site. The variation may be present in one or more samples.”
eval_28 %>% 
  plot_filter_density(var = qd, plot_title = "Density of QD values, chromosome 28") + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 10, color = "red")

Fisher strand

  • “Strand bias is a type of sequencing bias in which one DNA strand is favored over the other, which can result in incorrect evaluation of the amount of evidence observed for one allele vs. the other. The output is a Phred-scaled p-value. The higher the output value, the more likely there is to be bias. More bias is indicative of false positive calls. FisherStrand is best suited for low coverage situations. For testing strand bias in higher coverage situations, see the StrandOddsRatio annotation.”
  • Have used FS > 60 in the past
eval_28 %>% 
  plot_filter_density(var = fs, plot_title = "Density of FS values, chromosome 28") + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 60, color = "red")

The GATK team reccomends log(10) scaling the x-axis when plotting FS:

eval_28 %>% 
  plot_filter_density(var = fs, plot_title = "Density of FS values, chromosome 28") +
  scale_x_continuous(trans = 'log10') +
  labs(x = "log10(FS)")

RMS mapping quality

  • “Root mean square mapping quality provides an estimation of the overall mapping quality of reads supporting a variant call, averaged over all samples in a cohort.”

What percentage of SNPs actually were dropped?

nocalls %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_wider(values_from = no_call, names_from = dataset) %>% 
  summarise(`Percent dropped` = sum(is.na(demo_post))/sum(!is.na(demo_pre)))

How many SNPs were actually set to missing by genotype-level filtering?

nocalls %>% 
  filter(!is.na(no_call)) %>% 
  mutate(percent_missing = 
           case_when(
             dataset == "demo_post" ~ no_call/2362,
             dataset == "demo_pre" ~ no_call/2764,
             stringr::str_detect(dataset, "1kbulls") ~ no_call/4931
             )) %>% 
  group_by(dataset) %>% 
  summarise(`Min missing` = min(percent_missing),
            `Max missing` = max(percent_missing),
            `Avg missing` = mean(percent_missing))
nocalls %>% 
  mutate(percent_missing = 
           case_when(
             dataset == "demo_post" ~ no_call/2362,
             dataset == "demo_pre" ~ no_call/2764,
             stringr::str_detect(dataset, "1kbulls") ~ no_call/4931
             )) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = percent_missing)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap(~ dataset, nrow = 2, scales = "free_y")

Re-evaluate starting genotype quality using 5,000 randomly selected chromosome 28 SNPs

  • “GQ represents the Phred-scaled confidence that the genotype assignment (GT) is correct, derived from the genotype PLs. Specifically, the GQ is the difference between the PL of the second most likely genotype, and the PL of the most likely genotype. Basically the GQ gives you the difference between the likelihoods of the two most likely genotypes. If it is low, you can tell there is not much confidence in the genotype, i.e. there was not enough evidence to confidently choose one genotype over another.”

Summary across all sites and all individuals

gq %>% 
  filter(stringr::str_detect(dataset, "demo")) %>%
  plot_filter_density(gq) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 20, color = "red") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 13, color = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Density of GQ values, all genotypes at all sites")

Using 20

gq %>% 
  filter(stringr::str_detect(dataset, "demo")) %>% 
  mutate(gq = if_else(20 > gq, NA_integer_, as.integer(gq))) %>% 
  group_by(dataset) %>% 
  summarise(`% genotypes with GQ < 20` = sum(is.na(gq))/(sum(is.na(gq))+sum(!is.na(gq))))

Using 13

gq %>% 
  filter(stringr::str_detect(dataset, "demo")) %>% 
  mutate(gq = if_else(13 > gq, NA_integer_, as.integer(gq))) %>% 
  group_by(dataset) %>% 
  summarise(`% genotypes with GQ < 13` = sum(is.na(gq))/(sum(is.na(gq))+sum(!is.na(gq))))

Summary averaged by site

gq %>%

  ungroup() %>%

  geom_vline(xintercept = 20, color = "red") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 13, color = "blue") +

How many sites where > 10% of samples fail based on GQ?

gqtotal <-
  gq %>% 
  filter(dataset == "demo_pre") %>% 
  distinct(pos) %>% 
  pull(pos) %>% 
  length(.)
gqfail20 <-
  gq %>% 
  filter(dataset == "demo_pre") %>% 
  mutate(dropped = if_else(20 > gq, "TRUE", NA_character_)) %>% 
  group_by(pos) %>% 
  summarise(percent_fail = sum(!is.na(dropped))/(sum(!is.na(dropped))+sum(is.na(dropped)))) %>%
  filter(percent_fail > 0.1) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  pull(pos) %>% 
  length(.)
gqfail13 <-
  gq %>% 
  filter(dataset == "demo_pre") %>% 
  mutate(dropped = if_else(13 > gq, "TRUE", NA_character_)) %>% 
  group_by(pos) %>% 
  summarise(percent_fail = sum(!is.na(dropped))/(sum(!is.na(dropped))+sum(is.na(dropped)))) %>%
  filter(percent_fail > 0.1) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  pull(pos) %>% 
  length(.)

Using GQ cutoff of 20, 100.0% of variants would be removed. Using GQ cutoff of 13, 99.1% of variants would be removed.

Problem samples?

gq_demo <-
  gq %>% 
  filter(dataset == "demo_pre") %>% 
  left_join(sample_metadata %>% 
              select(international_id, population, species)) %>% 
  mutate(removed = if_else(is.na(population), "yes", "no"))

What if I took out samples with median GQ < 13?

  • As expected, this ends up being by my far removed outgroup samples
gq_demo %>% 
  group_by(international_id, removed, population, species) %>% 
  summarise(median = median(gq, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(removed == "no") %>% 
  filter(13 > median) %>% 
  group_by(population) %>% 
  tally(sort = TRUE)
gq_demo %>% 
  group_by(international_id, removed, population, species) %>% 
  summarise(median = median(gq, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(removed == "no") %>% 
  filter(13 > median) %>% 
  filter(species %in% c("bos taurus", "bos grunniens", "bos mutus", "bos indicus", "composite")) %>% 
  select(international_id) %>% 
  write_tsv(here::here("data/derived_data/joint_genotyping/filter_eval/remove_gq.txt"))
drop <-
  gq_demo %>% 
  group_by(international_id, removed, population, species) %>% 
  summarise(median = median(gq, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  filter(removed == "no") %>% 
  filter(13 > median) %>% 
  filter(!population %in% c("ancient"))
  • Even if I do remove those outgroup samples, I still theoretically would remove ~half of sites due to missingness
gq_demo %>% 
  filter(removed == "no") %>% 
  filter(!international_id %in% drop$international_id) %>% 
  mutate(dropped = if_else(13 > gq, "TRUE", NA_character_)) %>% 
  group_by(pos) %>% 
  summarise(percent_fail = sum(!is.na(dropped))/(sum(!is.na(dropped))+sum(is.na(dropped)))) %>%
  filter(percent_fail > 0.1) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  pull(pos) %>% 
  length(.)
